# Error Handling and Logging Rules

## Error categories

Use structured categories: `validation`, `authentication`, `authorization`, `network`, `timeout`, `configuration`, `integration`, `data`, `gameRuntime`, `firebase`, `security`, `unknown`.

## Every error path must define

- Technical error code
- User-safe message
- Log severity
- Retry eligibility
- Whether support action is required
- Whether audit logging is required

## Prohibited

- Ignoring errors or empty catch blocks
- Returning null for every failure
- Displaying stack traces to users
- Vague "Something went wrong" when a safer specific message exists
- Infinite retries
- Treating security failures as normal network errors

## Log levels

`debug`, `info`, `warning`, `error`, `critical` — reduce debug in production.

## Structured log fields (where relevant)

`environment`, `application`, `module`, `operation`, `requestId`, `sessionId`, `playerIdHash`, `institutionId`, `gameId`, `gameVersion`, `tournamentId`, `errorCode`

Avoid logging sensitive personal identifiers directly.

## Flutter

- Map errors to user-safe messages
- Integrate crash reporting where enabled
- Suppress debug logging in production
- No uncontrolled `print()` in production code

## Unity

- Avoid per-frame logging
- Use consistent categories; include game and protocol versions
- Report bridge failures clearly; avoid private session payloads in logs

## Firebase Functions

Use structured logger APIs. Critical operations: start/success/failure logs, correlation ID, duration where useful.

## Review checklist

- [ ] All failure paths handled
- [ ] User-safe messages defined
- [ ] No sensitive data in logs
- [ ] Audit logging for privileged failures where required
